README — Day-27 (Edge-Case Testing)
Objective

Enhance the verification environment by introducing directed edge-case tests in addition to random stimulus.

Random testing explores a wide input space, but it may miss critical boundary conditions.

Edge-case testing ensures that the design behaves correctly under extreme input values.

Edge Cases Tested

The ALU verification now includes the following boundary scenarios:

1️⃣ Zero Inputs
A = 0
B = 0

This verifies behavior when both operands are zero.

2️⃣ Maximum Inputs
A = 255
B = 255

Tests the ALU with maximum 8-bit values.

3️⃣ Overflow Scenario
A = 255
B = 1

Checks behavior when addition may overflow.

Generator Update

The generator now produces two types of stimulus:

Random transactions
Directed edge-case transactions

Workflow:

repeat(100) → random tests
+3 directed edge cases
Verification Pipeline
Generator → Driver → DUT
                       ↓
                    Monitor
                       ↓
                    Scoreboard

Edge cases pass through the same verification pipeline as random tests.

Benefits

Edge-case testing improves verification quality by:

ensuring boundary values are tested
detecting overflow conditions
validating zero-result scenarios
strengthening confidence in design correctness
Skills Achieved (Day-27)

You now understand:

directed testing
edge-case verification
boundary-value testing
combining random and directed tests
